[2
Date: Mon, 03 May 1999 09:52:59 +0200
From: David Basckin <kingbee@iafrica.com>
Source: Mail & Guardian on-line, Johannesburg, 3 May 1999 [edited

Dr Stephen Toovey, the director of the independent information service Medinfo, said the DRC
health ministry had reported to the WHO that another 20 people were infected with the deadly
virus. Toovey said there were also indications that the epidemic, which began in the rebel-
controlled northeast of the war-torn DRC, was spreading to the country's border with Sudan. He
said according to health workers in the area people were now succumbing to the virus in Faridje,
some 50km from the Sudanese border. "In this situation that (distance) is very little. There is a very
real danger of it spreading to Sudan," he said.
