[3
Date: Mon, 03 May 1999 11:21:14 -0400
From: "Marjorie P. Pollack" <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Reuters, 3 May 1999 [edited

Ebola-like fever kills 63 in Kabila's Congo
---------------------------------------------------
An Ebola-like haemorrhagic fever has killed at least 63 people in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo, health officials said on Monday.
The fever, which causes profuse bleeding like Ebola, surfaced in January near the town of Watsa in
the north east of the country, formerly known as Zaire, near the border with Uganda and Sudan.
A World Health Organisation official in the capital Kinshasa said that it was difficult to give a
reliable toll because of the possibility of double counting but he said that at least 63 sufferers had
died. A team from the Medecins Sans Frontieres medical charity had gone to the region, he added.
The dead in this year's fever outbreak included the doctor who reported and treated the first cases.
He died on 23 Apr 1999 in Isiro, which is in the same Oriental Province as Watsa.
Health Minister Mashako Mamba said on Sunday that reports were coming in of many dead in
remote villages. He spoke of dozens of deaths in a place called Durba. Health officials said that
these were among the 63 deaths reported thus far. Mashako said earlier that more cases and deaths
had been reported in Faradje to the north, which he described as the epicentre of the outbreak.
The cause of the latest outbreak was not immediately clear. Scientists have linked Ebola outbreaks
elsewhere to people who ate or handled monkeys who had died of the disease.
